3 Sac and Fox;
4 (7) a rural water district;
5 (8) a state conservation district;
6 (9) an organization that focuses on environmental or wildlife
7 protection or conservation;
8 (10) a local water management entity, including, but not limited to, a
9 groundwater management district, water assurance district or ditch district;
10 (11) the Kansas agricultural banking or appraisal industry;
11 (12) a student at a state educational institution engaged in a course of
12 study related to water;
13 (13) a Kansas municipality;
14 (14) a provider of natural resources education;
15 (15) the Kansas agricultural commodity associations;
16 (16) the Kansas water authority or regional advisory committee;
17 (17) the Kansas livestock industry; or
18 (18) the Kansas grain and feed industry.
19 (c) (1) Members of the task force shall be residents of Kansas. The
20 task force shall consist of at least two members from all five conservation
21 regions of the state. Not more than two members of the task force shall
22 represent the same stakeholder enumerated in subsection (b).
23 (2) The speaker of the house of representatives and the president of
24 the senate shall ensure that the requirements of paragraph (1) are met.
25 (d) Members of the task force shall be appointed by April 30, 2025.
26 Any vacancy in the membership of the task force shall be filled by
27 appointment in the same manner prescribed by this section for the original
28 appointment.
29 (e) The speaker of the house of representatives shall select one
30 member of the task force who is a member of the house of representatives
31 to serve as co-chairperson of the task force. The president of the senate
32 shall select one member of the task force who is a member of the senate to
33 serve as co-chairperson of the task force.
34 (f) (1) The task force may meet at any time and at any place within
35 the state upon the call of either co-chairperson.
36 (2) A majority of voting members shall constitute a quorum of the
37 task force. All actions of the task force may be taken by a majority of
38 members present when there is a quorum.
39 (3) If approved by the legislative coordinating council, members of
40 the task force attending meetings authorized by the task force shall be paid
41 amounts for expenses, mileage and subsistence as provided in K.S.A. 75-
42 3223(e), and amendments thereto.
43 (4) The staff of the office of revisor of statutes, the legislative

HB 2172 4
1 research department and the division of legislative administrative services
2 shall provide such assistance as may be requested by the task force.
3 (g) The water program task force shall:
4 (1) Evaluate major risks to the quality and quantity of the state's
5 water supply, including any impact on current and future economic growth
6 and population stability;
7 (2) steps that the state must take to define and achieve an ongoing,
8 multigenerational promise of water for Kansans; and
9 (3) evaluate current funding for water in the state and determine
10 whether such funding is sufficient to address the water issues included in
11 the state water plan, including the state's current and future water
12 infrastructure needs.
13 (h) The task force shall prepare and submit a report to the legislature
14 and the governor on or before January 31, 2026. Such report shall include
15 recommendations on:
16 (1) The water program's long-term structure to address the state's
17 current and future water needs, including, but not limited to:
18 (A) The roles and responsibilities of the state, municipalities and
19 regional entities;
20 (B) how the program's investments and successes should be
21 evaluated, including gathering any stakeholder input; and
22 (C) criteria to determine program investments, including geographic
23 diversity of such investments; and
24 (2) funding for the water program, including, but not limited to:
25 (A) New dedicated moneys or investments for the state water plan
26 fund;
27 (B) changes to any existing fees or moneys dedicated to the state
28 water plan fund; and
29 (C) any additional funding sources or tools necessary to ensure that
30 the financial resources are adequate to address the state's water issues.
31 (i) This section shall expire on July 1, 2027.
32 Sec. 2. This act shall take effect and be in force from and after its
33 publication in the Kansas register.

